\q2 …
\s1 The suffering servant
\p
\v 13 Listen, my servant will prosper—
\q1 he’ll be \add promoted and highly honoured\add*.
\q1
\v 14 Many people were horrified at you—his appearance was so disfigured
\q1 and his body \add was so disfigured\add* \add that he no longer looked like a man\add*.
\q1
\v 15 So he’ll startle many nations.
\q1 Kings will shut their mouths because even if they hadn’t been told about it,
\q1 they’ll see and understand what they hadn’t heard about.\x + \xo 52:15: \xt Rom 15:21.\x*
\c 53
\p
\v 1 Who has believed our message,\x + \xo 53:1: \xt Rom 10:16; Yhn 12:38.\x*
\q1 and who has Yahweh’s \add power\add* been revealed to?
\q1
\v 2 He grew in front of him like a young plant,
\q1 and like a root out of the dry ground.
\q1 He had no \add fancy\add* form or splendour to look at,
\q1 and his appearance \add didn’t attract us to him\add*.
\q1
\v 3 He was despised and rejected by people—
\q1 a man \add with a lot of\add* pain and familiar with sickness
\q1 like someone that \add most people would look away from\add*
\q1 and despise him, \add rather than to\add* esteem him.
\b
\q1
\v 4 \add Despite that\add*, he’s borne our sicknesses
\q1 and carried our sorrows.
\q1 We \add thought\add* that he’d been struck down by God—
\q1 attacked and made to suffer.\x + \xo 53:4: \xt Mat 8:17.\x*
\q1
\v 5 \add But\add* he was pierced for our disobedience,
\q1 and crushed for our wicked actions.
\q1 The punishment that \add gave us\add* peace was on him,
\q1 and we were healed \add thanks\add* to his wounds.\x + \xo 53:5: \xt 1Pe 2:24.\x*
\q1
\v 6 We’ve all strayed away like sheep—
\q1 \add everyone’s gone in their own direction\add*
\q1 and Yahweh has placed all our disobedience onto him.\x + \xo 53:6: \xt 1Pe 2:25.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 7 He was oppressed and tormented
\q1 \add but\add* like a lamb being led away to be slaughtered, he didn’t open his mouth,
\q1 and like a sheep that’s silent in front of its shearers, he didn’t open his mouth.\x + \xo 53:7: \xt Rev 5:6.\x*
\q1
\v 8 \add After\add* oppression and judgement, he was taken away,
\q1 \add but how many of his peers even cared\add* that he was cut off from the land of the living?
\q1 He was wounded because of the disobedience of my people.
\q1
\v 9 His burial place was among the criminals,
\q1 and a rich man at his death,
\q1 although he’d committed no violent acts,
\q1 and \add had never spoken deceitfully\add*.\x + \xo 53:9: \xt 1Pe 2:22.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 10 \add But\add* Yahweh desired to crush him—
\q1 he made him sick if it would make his life a guilt offering.
\q1 He will live long and see offspring,
\q1 and Yahweh’ plans will prosper \add through his work\add*.
\q1
\v 11 Due to his internal anguish, he’ll be able to see.
\q1 He’ll be satisfied with his knowledge.
\q1 My \add obedient\add* servant will justify many,
\q1 and he will carry their disobedience.
\q1
\v 12 \add Because of that,\add* I’ll allocate a portion for him.
\q1 He’ll divide out the plunder to a powerful people
\q1 because he poured out his life \add resulting in\add* his death.
\q1 He was included with the wicked,
\q1 and he bore the disobedience of many people,
\q1 and he intervened on behalf of the disobedient.\x + \xo 53:12: \xt Luk 22:37.\x*
\c 54
\s1 The love of God of Yerushalem
\p
